# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rotary-position-embedding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] "**Attention Is All You Need**" is a 2017 research paper in machine learning authored by eight scientists and engineers working at Google.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving Seq2seq techniques for machine translation, but the authors went further in the paper, foreseeing the technique's potential for other tasks like question answering and what is now known as multimodal generative AI.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Some early examples that the team tried their Transformer architecture on included English-to-German translation, generating Wikipedia articles on "The Transformer", and parsing.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] These convinced the team that the Transformer is a general-purpose language model, and not just good for translation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] As of 2026, the paper has been cited more than 250,000 times, placing it among the top ten most-cited papers of the 21st century.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] After the paper was published by Google, each of the eight authors left the company to join other companies or to found startups.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The authors of the paper are Ashish Vaswani, Noam Shazeer, Niki Parmar, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, Aidan Gomez, Łukasz Kaiser, and Illia Polosukhin.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] All eight authors were "equal contributors" to the paper; the listed order was randomized (according to the paper itself).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] After the paper, each of the authors left Google to join other companies or to found startups.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The paper's title is a reference to the song "All You Need Is Love" by the Beatles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The name "Transformer" was picked because Jakob Uszkoreit, one of the paper's authors, liked the sound of that word.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] An early design document was titled "Transformers: Iterative Self-Attention and Processing for Various Tasks", and included an illustration of six characters from the *Transformers* franchise.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The paper is best known for introducing the Transformer architecture, which underlies most modern large language models (LLMs).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] A key reason why the architecture is preferred by most modern LLMs is the parallelizability of the architecture over its predecessors.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] This ensures that the operations necessary for training can be accelerated on a GPU, allowing both faster training times and models of bigger sizes to be trained.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The paper introduced the following mechanisms as part of the development of the transformer architecture.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The use of the scaled dot-product attention and self-attention mechanism instead of a recurrent neural network (RNN) or long short-term memory (which rely on recurrence) allows for better performance as described in the following paragraph.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] where Q , K , V are respectively the query, key, value matrices, and $d_{k}$ is the dimension of the values.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Since the model relies on Query (*Q*), Key (*K*), and Value (*V*) matrices that come from the same source (i.e., the input sequence or context window), this eliminates the need for RNNs, completely ensuring parallelizability for the architecture.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] This differs from the original form of the Attention mechanism introduced in 2014.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Additionally, the paper discusses the use of an additional scaling factor that was found to be most effective with respect to the dimension of the key vectors (represented as $d_{k}$ and initially set to 64 within the paper) in the manner shown above.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In the specific context of translation, which the paper focused on, the Query and Key matrices are usually represented in embeddings corresponding to the source language, while the Value matrix corresponds to the target language.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In the self-attention mechanism, queries (Q), keys (K), and values (V) are dynamically generated for each input sequence (typically limited by the size of the context window), allowing the model to focus on different parts of the input sequence at different steps.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Multi-head attention enhances this process by introducing multiple parallel attention heads.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Each attention head learns different linear projections of the Q, K, and V matrices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] This allows the model to capture different aspects of the relationships between words in the sequence simultaneously, rather than focusing on a single aspect.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] By doing this, multi-head attention ensures that the input embeddings are updated from a more varied and diverse set of perspectives.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] After the attention outputs from all heads are calculated, they are concatenated and passed through a final linear transformation to generate the output.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Since the Transformer does not rely on recurrence or convolution of the text in order to perform encoding and decoding, the paper relied on the use of sine and cosine wave functions to encode the position of the token into the embedding.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] wherein ${\rm {pos}}$ , i , ${d_{\rm {model}}}$ correspond to the position of the word, the current dimension index, and the dimension of the model, respectively.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The sine function is used for even indices of the embedding while the cosine function is used for odd indices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The resultant $PE$ embedding is then added to the word at that corresponding position with respect to the current context window.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-is-all-you-need] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In linear algebra, a **rotation matrix** is a transformation matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] rotates points in the xy plane counterclockwise through an angle θ about the origin of a two-dimensional Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] One way to understand this is to say we have a vector at an angle 30° from the x-axis, and we wish to rotate that angle by a further 45°.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] We simply need to compute the vector endpoint coordinates at 75°.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The examples in this article apply to *active rotations* of vectors *counterclockwise* in a *right-handed coordinate system* (y counterclockwise from x) by *pre-multiplication* (the rotation matrix R applied on the left of the column vector **v** to be rotated).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If any one of these is changed (such as rotating axes instead of vectors, a *passive transformation*), then the inverse of the example matrix should be used, which coincides with its transpose.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices describe rotations about the origin.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Rotation matrices provide an algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In some literature, the term *rotation* is generalized to include improper rotations, characterized by orthogonal matrices with a determinant of −1 (instead of +1).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] An improper rotation combines a *proper* rotation with *reflections* (which invert orientation).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In other cases, where reflections are not being considered, the label *proper* may be dropped.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The latter convention is followed in this article.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] More specifically, they can be characterized as orthogonal matrices with determinant 1; that is, a square matrix *R* is a rotation matrix if and only if *R*T = *R*−1 and det *R* = 1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The set of all orthogonal matrices of size n with determinant +1 is a representation of a group known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*), one example of which is the rotation group SO(3).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The set of all orthogonal matrices of size n with determinant +1 or −1 is a representation of the (general) orthogonal group O(*n*).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The sense or "direction" of vector rotation (not to be confused with the vector direction) is counterclockwise if θ is positive (e.g.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] An alternative convention uses rotating axes (instead of rotating a vector), and the above matrices also represent a rotation of the *axes clockwise* through an angle θ.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The two-dimensional case is the only non-trivial case where the rotation matrices group is commutative; it does not matter in which order rotations are multiply performed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If a standard right-handed Cartesian coordinate system is used, with the x-axis to the right and the y-axis up, the rotation *R*(*θ*) is counterclockwise.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If a left-handed Cartesian coordinate system is used, with x directed to the right but y directed down, *R*(*θ*) is clockwise.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Such non-standard orientations are rarely used in mathematics but are common in 2D computer graphics, which often have the origin in the top left corner and the y-axis down the screen or page.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] See below for other alternative conventions which may change the sense of the rotation produced by a rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The matrices of the shape ${\begin{bmatrix}x&-y\\y&x\end{bmatrix}}$ form a ring, since their set is closed under addition and multiplication.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In other words, a vector rotation corresponds to multiplication on a complex number (corresponding to the vector being rotated) by a complex number of modulus 1 (corresponding to the rotation matrix).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] A basic 3D rotation (also called elemental rotation) is a rotation about one of the axes of a coordinate system.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The following three basic rotation matrices rotate vectors by an angle θ about the x-, y-, or z-axis, in three dimensions, using the right-hand rule—which codifies their alternating signs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Notice that the right-hand rule only works when multiplying $R\cdot {\vec {x}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The same matrices can also represent a clockwise rotation of the axes keeping the vectors unchanged.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For column vectors, each of these basic vector rotations appears counterclockwise when the axis about which they occur points toward the observer, the coordinate system is right-handed, and the angle θ is positive.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This is similar to the rotation produced by the above-mentioned two-dimensional rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] See below for alternative conventions which may apparently or actually invert the sense of the rotation produced by these matrices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Other 3D rotation matrices can be obtained from these three using matrix multiplication.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] represents a rotation whose yaw, pitch, and roll angles are α, β and γ, respectively.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] More formally, it is an intrinsic rotation whose Tait–Bryan angles are α, β, γ, about axes z, y, x, respectively.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] These matrices produce the desired effect only if they are used to premultiply column vectors, and (since in general matrix multiplication is not commutative) only if they are applied in the specified order (see Ambiguities for more details).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The order of rotation operations is from right to left; the matrix adjacent to the column vector is the first to be applied, and then the one to the left.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Every rotation in three dimensions is defined by its **axis** (a vector along this axis is unchanged by the rotation), and its **angle** — the amount of rotation about that axis (Euler rotation theorem).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] There are several methods to compute the axis and angle from a rotation matrix (see also axis–angle representation).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Here, we only describe the method based on the computation of the eigenvectors and eigenvalues of the rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] It is also possible to use the trace of the rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Given a 3 × 3 rotation matrix R, a vector **u** parallel to the rotation axis must satisfy $R\mathbf {u} =\mathbf {u} ,$ since the rotation of **u** around the rotation axis must result in **u**.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The equation above may be solved for **u** which is unique up to a scalar factor unless R is the identity matrix I.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Further, the equation may be rewritten $R\mathbf {u} =I\mathbf {u} \implies \left(R-I\right)\mathbf {u} =0,$ which shows that **u** lies in the null space of *R* − *I*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This means precisely that that **u** is an eigenvector of R corresponding to the eigenvalue *λ* = 1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Every rotation matrix must have this eigenvalue, the other two eigenvalues being complex conjugates of each other.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] It follows that a general rotation matrix in three dimensions has, up to a multiplicative constant, only one real eigenvector.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Therefore, if $R={\begin{bmatrix}a&b&c\\d&e&f\\g&h&i\\\end{bmatrix}},$ then $\mathbf {u} ={\begin{bmatrix}h-f\\c-g\\d-b\\\end{bmatrix}}.$ The magnitude of **u** computed this way is ‖**u**‖ = 2 sin *θ*, where θ is the angle of rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This **does not work** if R is symmetric.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Above, if *R* − *R*T is zero, then all subsequent steps are invalid.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In this case, the angle of rotation is 0° or 180° and any nonzero column of *I* + *R* is an eigenvector of R with eigenvalue 1 because *R*(*I* + *R*) = *R* + *R*2 = *R* + *RR*T = *I* + *R*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] To find the angle of a rotation, once the axis of the rotation is known, select a vector **v** perpendicular to the axis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Then the angle of the rotation is the angle between **v** and *R***v**.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] A more direct method, however, is to simply calculate the **trace**: the sum of the diagonal elements of the rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] A derivation of this matrix from first principles can be found in section 9.2 here.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The basic idea to derive this matrix is dividing the problem into few known simple steps.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Use one of the fundamental rotation matrices to rotate the point depending on the coordinate axis with which the rotation axis is aligned.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This can be written more concisely as $R=(\cos \theta )\,I+(\sin \theta )\,[\mathbf {u} ]_{\times }+(1-\cos \theta )\,(\mathbf {u} \otimes \mathbf {u} ),$ where [**u**]× is the cross product matrix of **u**; the expression **u** ⊗ **u** is the outer product, and I is the identity matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] where εjkl is the Levi-Civita symbol with *ε*123 = 1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If the 3D space is right-handed and *θ* > 0, this rotation will be counterclockwise when **u** points towards the observer (Right-hand rule).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Note the striking *merely apparent differences* to the *equivalent* Lie-algebraic formulation below.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] A rotation is termed proper if det *R* = 1, and improper (or a roto-reflection) if det *R* = –1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For even dimensions *n* = 2*k*, the n eigenvalues λ of a proper rotation occur as pairs of complex conjugates which are roots of unity: *λ* = *e*±*iθj* for *j* = 1, ..., *k*, which is real only for *λ* = ±1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Therefore, there may be no vectors fixed by the rotation (*λ* = 1), and thus no axis of rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Any fixed eigenvectors occur in pairs, and the axis of rotation is an even-dimensional subspace.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For odd dimensions *n* = 2*k* + 1, a proper rotation R will have an odd number of eigenvalues, with at least one *λ* = 1 and the axis of rotation will be an odd dimensional subspace.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Here I is the identity matrix, and we use det(*R*T) = det(*R*) = 1, as well as (−1)*n* = −1 since n is odd.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] There may also be pairs of fixed eigenvectors in the even-dimensional subspace orthogonal to **v**, so the total dimension of fixed eigenvectors is odd.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For example, in 2-space *n* = 2, a rotation by angle θ has eigenvalues *λ* = *eiθ* and *λ* = *e*−*iθ*, so there is no axis of rotation except when *θ* = 0, the case of the null rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In 3-space *n* = 3, the axis of a non-null proper rotation is always a unique line, and a rotation around this axis by angle θ has eigenvalues *λ* = 1, *eiθ*, *e*−*iθ*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In 4-space *n* = 4, the four eigenvalues are of the form *e*±*iθ*, *e*±*iφ*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The case of *θ* = 0, *φ* ≠ 0 is called a *simple rotation*, with two unit eigenvalues forming an *axis plane*, and a two-dimensional rotation orthogonal to the axis plane.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The case of *θ* = *φ* is called an *isoclinic rotation*, having eigenvalues *e*±*iθ* repeated twice, so every vector is rotated through an angle θ.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The trace of a rotation matrix is equal to the sum of its eigenvalues.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For *n* = 2, a rotation by angle θ has trace 2 cos *θ*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For *n* = 3, a rotation around any axis by angle θ has trace 1 + 2 cos *θ*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For *n* = 4, and the trace is 2(cos *θ* + cos *φ*), which becomes 4 cos *θ* for an isoclinic rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In Euclidean geometry, a rotation is an example of an isometry, a transformation that moves points without changing the distances between them.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Rotations are distinguished from other isometries by two additional properties: they leave (at least) one point fixed, and they leave "handedness" unchanged.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In contrast, a translation moves every point, a reflection exchanges left- and right-handed ordering, a glide reflection does both, and an improper rotation combines a change in handedness with a normal rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If a fixed point is taken as the origin of a Cartesian coordinate system, then every point can be given coordinates as a displacement from the origin.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Thus one may work with the vector space of displacements instead of the points themselves.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Now suppose (*p*1, ..., *pn*) are the coordinates of the vector **p** from the origin O to point P.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] A geometric rotation transforms lines to lines, and preserves ratios of distances between points.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] From these properties it can be shown that a rotation is a linear transformation of the vectors, and thus can be written in matrix form, *Q***p**.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This means that multiplication of rotation matrices corresponds to composition of rotations, applied in left-to-right order of their corresponding matrices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The interpretation of a rotation matrix can be subject to many ambiguities.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In most cases the effect of the ambiguity is equivalent to the effect of a rotation matrix inversion (for these orthogonal matrices equivalently matrix transpose).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Any given rotation can be legitimately described both ways, as vectors and coordinate systems actually rotate with respect to each other, about the same axis but in opposite directions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Throughout this article, we chose the alibi approach to describe rotations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] by the same angle but in the opposite direction (i.e. clockwise).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Throughout this article, rotations produced on column vectors are described by means of a pre-multiplication.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Throughout the article, we assumed a right-handed orientation, unless otherwise specified.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] , and the matrix can act on either vectors or forms.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] First, one of the roots (or eigenvalues) is 1, which tells us that some direction is unaffected by the matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For rotations in three dimensions, this is the *axis* of the rotation (a concept that has no meaning in any other dimension).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Second, the other two roots are a pair of complex conjugates, whose product is 1 (the constant term of the quadratic), and whose sum is 2 cos *θ* (the negated linear term).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This factorization is of interest for 3 × 3 rotation matrices because the same thing occurs for all of them.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] (As special cases, for a null rotation the "complex conjugates" are both 1, and for a 180° rotation they are both −1.) Furthermore, a similar factorization holds for any *n* × *n* rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If the dimension, n, is odd, there will be a "dangling" eigenvalue of 1; and for any dimension the rest of the polynomial factors into quadratic terms like the one here (with the two special cases noted).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] We are guaranteed that the characteristic polynomial will have degree n and thus n eigenvalues.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] And since a rotation matrix commutes with its transpose, it is a normal matrix, so can be diagonalized.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] We conclude that every rotation matrix, when expressed in a suitable coordinate system, partitions into independent rotations of two-dimensional subspaces, at most ⁠*n*/2⁠ of them.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The sum of the entries on the main diagonal of a matrix is called the trace; it does not change if we reorient the coordinate system, and always equals the sum of the eigenvalues.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This has the convenient implication for 2 × 2 and 3 × 3 rotation matrices that the trace reveals the angle of rotation, θ, in the two-dimensional space (or subspace).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] For a 2 × 2 matrix the trace is 2 cos *θ*, and for a 3 × 3 matrix it is 1 + 2 cos *θ*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In the three-dimensional case, the subspace consists of all vectors perpendicular to the rotation axis (the invariant direction, with eigenvalue 1).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Thus we can extract from any 3 × 3 rotation matrix a rotation axis and an angle, and these completely determine the rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The constraints on a 2 × 2 rotation matrix imply that it must have the form $Q={\begin{bmatrix}a&-b\\b&a\end{bmatrix}}$ with *a*2 + *b*2 = 1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Therefore, we may set *a* = cos *θ* and *b* = sin *θ*, for some angle θ.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] To solve for θ it is not enough to look at a alone or b alone; we must consider both together to place the angle in the correct quadrant, using a two-argument arctangent function.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This acts on the subspace spanned by the x- and y-axes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] We can then repeat the process for the xz-subspace to zero c.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Acting on the full matrix, these two rotations produce the schematic form $Q_{xz}Q_{xy}Q={\begin{bmatrix}1&0&0\\0&\ast &\ast \\0&\ast &\ast \end{bmatrix}}.$ Shifting attention to the second column, a Givens rotation of the yz-subspace can now zero the z value.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] We can zero them by extending the same idea of stepping through the columns with a series of rotations in a fixed sequence of planes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] We conclude that the set of *n* × *n* rotation matrices, each of which has *n*2 entries, can be parameterized by ⁠1/2⁠*n*(*n* − 1) angles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In three dimensions this restates in matrix form an observation made by Euler, so mathematicians call the ordered sequence of three angles Euler angles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] However, the situation is somewhat more complicated than we have so far indicated.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Despite the small dimension, we actually have considerable freedom in the sequence of axis pairs we use; and we also have some freedom in the choice of angles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Thus we find many different conventions employed when three-dimensional rotations are parameterized for physics, or medicine, or chemistry, or other disciplines.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] When we include the option of world axes or body axes, 24 different sequences are possible.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] And while some disciplines call any sequence Euler angles, others give different names (Cardano, Tait–Bryan, roll-pitch-yaw) to different sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] One reason for the large number of options is that, as noted previously, rotations in three dimensions (and higher) do not commute.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If we reverse a given sequence of rotations, we get a different outcome.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This also implies that we cannot compose two rotations by adding their corresponding angles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Thus Euler angles are not vectors, despite a similarity in appearance as a triplet of numbers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This is no illusion; not just one, but many, copies of n-dimensional rotations are found within (*n* + 1)-dimensional rotations, as subgroups.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Each embedding leaves one direction fixed, which in the case of 3 × 3 matrices is the rotation axis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] fixing the x-axis, the y-axis, and the z-axis, respectively.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] where *cθ* = cos *θ*, *sθ* = sin *θ*, is a rotation by angle θ leaving axis **u** fixed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] A direction in (*n* + 1)-dimensional space will be a unit magnitude vector, which we may consider a point on a generalized sphere, *S**n*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Thus it is natural to describe the rotation group SO(*n* + 1) as combining SO(*n*) and *S**n*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] where for every direction in the base space, *S**n*, the fiber over it in the total space, SO(*n* + 1), is a copy of the fiber space, SO(*n*), namely the rotations that keep that direction fixed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Thus we can build an *n* × *n* rotation matrix by starting with a 2 × 2 matrix, aiming its fixed axis on *S*2 (the ordinary sphere in three-dimensional space), aiming the resulting rotation on *S*3, and so on up through *S**n*−1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] A point on *S**n* can be selected using n numbers, so we again have ⁠1/2⁠*n*(*n* − 1) numbers to describe any *n* × *n* rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In fact, we can view the sequential angle decomposition, discussed previously, as reversing this process.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The composition of *n* − 1 Givens rotations brings the first column (and row) to (1, 0, ..., 0), so that the remainder of the matrix is a rotation matrix of dimension one less, embedded so as to leave (1, 0, ..., 0) fixed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] When an *n* × *n* rotation matrix Q, does not include a −1 eigenvalue, thus none of the planar rotations which it comprises are 180° rotations, then *Q* + *I* is an invertible matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Most rotation matrices fit this description, and for them it can be shown that (*Q* − *I*)(*Q* + *I*)−1 is a skew-symmetric matrix, A.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Thus *A*T = −*A*; and since the diagonal is necessarily zero, and since the upper triangle determines the lower one, A contains ⁠1/2⁠*n*(*n* − 1) independent numbers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Conveniently, *I* − *A* is invertible whenever A is skew-symmetric; thus we can recover the original matrix using the *Cayley transform*, $A\mapsto (I+A)(I-A)^{-1},$ which maps any skew-symmetric matrix A to a rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] In fact, aside from the noted exceptions, we can produce any rotation matrix in this way.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] Although in practical applications we can hardly afford to ignore 180° rotations, the Cayley transform is still a potentially useful tool, giving a parameterization of most rotation matrices without trigonometric functions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] If we condense the skew entries into a vector, (*x*,*y*,*z*), then we produce a 90° rotation around the x-axis for (1, 0, 0), around the y-axis for (0, 1, 0), and around the z-axis for (0, 0, 1).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] The 180° rotations are just out of reach; for, in the limit as *x* → ∞, (*x*, 0, 0) does approach a 180° rotation around the x axis, and similarly for other directions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] This is useful, for instance, in computer graphics, since shears can be implemented with fewer multiplication instructions than rotating a bitmap directly.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p01] On modern computers, this may not matter, but it can be relevant for very old or low-end microprocessors.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Examples abound in classical mechanics and quantum mechanics.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Knowledge of the part of the solutions pertaining to this symmetry applies (with qualifications) to *all* such problems and it can be factored out of a specific problem at hand, thus reducing its complexity.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] A prime example – in mathematics and physics – would be the theory of spherical harmonics.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Their role in the group theory of the rotation groups is that of being a representation space for the entire set of finite-dimensional irreducible representations of the rotation group SO(3).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For this topic, see Rotation group SO(3) § Spherical harmonics.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The main articles listed in each subsection are referred to for more detail.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The *n* × *n* rotation matrices for each n form a group, the special orthogonal group, SO(*n*).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This algebraic structure is coupled with a topological structure inherited from $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(\mathbb {R} )$ in such a way that the operations of multiplication and taking the inverse are analytic functions of the matrix entries.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] It is compact and connected, but not simply connected.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] It is also a semi-simple group, in fact a simple group with the exception SO(4).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The relevance of this is that all theorems and all machinery from the theory of analytic manifolds (analytic manifolds are in particular smooth manifolds) apply and the well-developed representation theory of compact semi-simple groups is ready for use.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Connecting the Lie algebra to the Lie group is the exponential map, which is defined using the standard matrix exponential series for eA For any skew-symmetric matrix A, exp(*A*) is always a rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] An important practical example is the 3 × 3 case.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In rotation group SO(3), it is shown that one can identify every *A* ∈ **so**(3) with an Euler vector **ω** = *θ***u**, where **u** = (*x*, *y*, *z*) is a unit magnitude vector.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] By the properties of the identification $\mathbf {su} (2)\cong \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , **u** is in the null space of A.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Thus, **u** is left invariant by exp(*A*) and is hence a rotation axis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This is the matrix for a rotation around axis **u** by the angle θ.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For full detail, see exponential map SO(3).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The BCH formula provides an explicit expression for *Z* = log(*e**X**e**Y*) in terms of a series expansion of nested commutators of X and Y.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In the 3 × 3 case, the general infinite expansion has a compact form, $Z=\alpha X+\beta Y+\gamma [X,Y],$ for suitable trigonometric function coefficients, detailed in the Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff formula for SO(3).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] As a group identity, the above holds for *all faithful representations*, including the doublet (spinor representation), which is simpler.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The same explicit formula thus follows straightforwardly through Pauli matrices; see the 2 × 2 derivation for SU(2).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For the general *n* × *n* case, one might use Ref.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The Lie group of *n* × *n* rotation matrices, SO(*n*), is not simply connected, so Lie theory tells us it is a homomorphic image of a universal covering group.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Often the covering group, which in this case is called the spin group denoted by Spin(*n*), is simpler and more natural to work with.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In the case of planar rotations, SO(2) is topologically a circle, *S*1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Its universal covering group, Spin(2), is isomorphic to the real line, **R**, under addition.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Whenever angles of arbitrary magnitude are used one is taking advantage of the convenience of the universal cover.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Every 2 × 2 rotation matrix is produced by a countable infinity of angles, separated by integer multiples of 2π.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Correspondingly, the fundamental group of SO(2) is isomorphic to the integers, **Z**.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In the case of spatial rotations, SO(3) is topologically equivalent to three-dimensional real projective space, **RP**3.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Its universal covering group, Spin(3), is isomorphic to the 3-sphere, *S*3.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Every 3 × 3 rotation matrix is produced by two opposite points on the sphere.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Correspondingly, the fundamental group of SO(3) is isomorphic to the two-element group, **Z**2.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] We can also describe Spin(3) as isomorphic to quaternions of unit norm under multiplication, or to certain 4 × 4 real matrices, or to 2 × 2 complex special unitary matrices, namely SU(2).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For a detailed account of the SU(2)-covering and the quaternionic covering, see spin group SO(3).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Many features of these cases are the same for higher dimensions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The coverings are all two-to-one, with SO(*n*), *n* > 2, having fundamental group **Z**2.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The natural setting for these groups is within a Clifford algebra.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] One type of action of the rotations is produced by a kind of "sandwich", denoted by *qvq*∗.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] More importantly in applications to physics, the corresponding spin representation of the Lie algebra sits inside the Clifford algebra.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] It can be exponentiated in the usual way to give rise to a 2-valued representation, also known as projective representation of the rotation group.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This is the case with SO(3) and SU(2), where the 2-valued representation can be viewed as an "inverse" of the covering map.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] By properties of covering maps, the inverse can be chosen ono-to-one as a local section, but not globally.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The matrices in the Lie algebra are not themselves rotations; the skew-symmetric matrices are derivatives, proportional differences of rotations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The computation rules are as usual except that infinitesimals of second order are routinely dropped.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] With these rules, these matrices do not satisfy all the same properties as ordinary finite rotation matrices under the usual treatment of infinitesimals.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] It turns out that *the order in which infinitesimal rotations are applied is irrelevant*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] To see this exemplified, consult infinitesimal rotations SO(3).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] We have seen the existence of several decompositions that apply in any dimension, namely independent planes, sequential angles, and nested dimensions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In all these cases we can either decompose a matrix or construct one.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] We have also given special attention to 3 × 3 rotation matrices, and these warrant further attention, in both directions (Stuelpnagel 1964).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Now every quaternion component appears multiplied by two in a term of degree two, and if all such terms are zero what is left is an identity matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This leads to an efficient, robust conversion from any quaternion – whether unit or non-unit – to a 3 × 3 rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Freed from the demand for a unit quaternion, we find that nonzero quaternions act as homogeneous coordinates for 3 × 3 rotation matrices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The Cayley transform, discussed earlier, is obtained by scaling the quaternion so that its w component is 1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For a 180° rotation around any axis, w will be zero, which explains the Cayley limitation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The sum of the entries along the main diagonal (the trace), plus one, equals 4 − 4(*x*2 + *y*2 + *z*2), which is 4*w*2.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Thus we can write the trace itself as 2*w*2 + 2*w*2 − 1; and from the previous version of the matrix we see that the diagonal entries themselves have the same form: 2*x*2 + 2*w*2 − 1, 2*y*2 + 2*w*2 − 1, and 2*z*2 + 2*w*2 − 1.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] So we can easily compare the magnitudes of all four quaternion components using the matrix diagonal.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This is numerically stable so long as the trace, t, is not negative; otherwise, we risk dividing by (nearly) zero.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] (If Q is truly a rotation matrix, that value will be 1.) The quaternion so obtained will correspond to the rotation matrix closest to the given matrix (Bar-Itzhack 2000) (Note: formulation of the cited article is post-multiplied, works with row vectors).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] If the *n* × *n* matrix M is nonsingular, its columns are linearly independent vectors; thus the Gram–Schmidt process can adjust them to be an orthonormal basis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Stated in terms of numerical linear algebra, we convert M to an orthogonal matrix, Q, using QR decomposition.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] However, we often prefer a Q closest to M, which this method does not accomplish.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For that, the tool we want is the polar decomposition (Fan & Hoffman 1955; Higham 1989).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] To measure closeness, we may use any matrix norm invariant under orthogonal transformations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] A convenient choice is the Frobenius norm, ‖*Q* − *M*‖F, squared, which is the sum of the squares of the element differences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Though written in matrix terms, the objective function is just a quadratic polynomial.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] We can minimize it in the usual way, by finding where its derivative is zero.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For a 3 × 3 matrix, the orthogonality constraint implies six scalar equalities that the entries of Q must satisfy.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] To incorporate the constraint(s), we may employ a standard technique, Lagrange multipliers, assembled as a symmetric matrix, Y.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In general, we obtain the equation $0=2(Q-M)+2QY,$ so that $M=Q(I+Y)=QS,$ where Q is orthogonal and S is symmetric.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] To ensure a minimum, the Y matrix (and hence S) must be positive definite.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] When M is non-singular, the Q and S factors of the polar decomposition are uniquely determined.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] However, the determinant of S is positive because S is positive definite, so Q inherits the sign of the determinant of M.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] That is, Q is only guaranteed to be orthogonal, not a rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This is unavoidable; an M with negative determinant has no uniquely defined closest rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] To efficiently construct a rotation matrix Q from an angle θ and a unit axis **u**, we can take advantage of symmetry and skew-symmetry within the entries.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Determining an axis and angle, like determining a quaternion, is only possible up to the sign; that is, (**u**, *θ*) and (−**u**, −*θ*) correspond to the same rotation matrix, just like *q* and −*q*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Additionally, axis–angle extraction presents additional difficulties.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The angle can be restricted to be from 0° to 180°, but angles are formally ambiguous by multiples of 360°.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] When the angle is zero, the axis is undefined.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] When the angle is 180°, the matrix becomes symmetric, which has implications in extracting the axis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The x-, y-, and z-components of the axis would then be divided by r.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] A fully robust approach will use a different algorithm when t, the trace of the matrix Q, is negative, as with quaternion extraction.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] When r is zero because the angle is zero, an axis must be provided from some source other than the matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Complexity of conversion escalates with Euler angles (used here in the broad sense).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The first difficulty is to establish which of the twenty-four variations of Cartesian axis order we will use.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Among all permutations of (*x*,*y*,*z*), only two place that axis first; one is an even permutation and the other odd.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Choosing parity thus establishes the middle axis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] That leaves two choices for the left-most axis, either duplicating the first or not.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] These three choices gives us 3 × 2 × 2 = 12 variations; we double that to 24 by choosing static or rotating axes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This is enough to construct a matrix from angles, but triples differing in many ways can give the same rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Angles for any order can be found using a concise common routine (Herter & Lott 1993; Shoemake 1994).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The problem of singular alignment, the mathematical analog of physical gimbal lock, occurs when the middle rotation aligns the axes of the first and last rotations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] It afflicts every axis order at either even or odd multiples of 90°.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] These singularities are not characteristic of the rotation matrix as such, and only occur with the usage of Euler angles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The singularities are avoided when considering and manipulating the rotation matrix as orthonormal row vectors (in 3D applications often named the right-vector, up-vector and out-vector) instead of as angles.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] The singularities are also avoided when working with quaternions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In some instances it is interesting to describe a rotation by specifying how a vector is mapped into another through the shortest path (smallest angle).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ this completely describes the associated rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In materials science, the four-dimensional stiffness and compliance tensors are often simplified to a two-dimensional matrix using Voigt notation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This is particularly useful in composite laminate design, where plies are often rotated by a certain angle to bring the properties of the laminate closer to isotropic.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] We sometimes need to generate a uniformly distributed random rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] It seems intuitively clear in two dimensions that this means the rotation angle is uniformly distributed between 0 and 2π.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] That intuition is correct, but does not carry over to higher dimensions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For example, if we decompose 3 × 3 rotation matrices in axis–angle form, the angle should *not* be uniformly distributed; the probability that (the magnitude of) the angle is at most θ should be ⁠1/π⁠(*θ* − sin *θ*), for 0 ≤ *θ* ≤ π.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Since SO(*n*) is a connected and locally compact Lie group, we have a simple standard criterion for uniformity, namely that the distribution be unchanged when composed with any arbitrary rotation (a Lie group "translation").
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This definition corresponds to what is called *Haar measure*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] León, Massé & Rivest (2006) show how to use the Cayley transform to generate and test matrices according to this criterion.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] We can also generate a uniform distribution in any dimension using the *subgroup algorithm* of Diaconis & Shahshahani (1987).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] This recursively exploits the nested dimensions group structure of SO(*n*), as follows.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Generate a uniform angle and construct a 2 × 2 rotation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] To step from *n* to *n* + 1, generate a vector **v** uniformly distributed on the n-sphere *S**n*, embed the *n* × *n* matrix in the next larger size with last column (0, ..., 0, 1), and rotate the larger matrix so the last column becomes **v**.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] As usual, we have special alternatives for the 3 × 3 case.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Each of these methods begins with three independent random scalars uniformly distributed on the unit interval.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Arvo (1992) takes advantage of the odd dimension to change a Householder reflection to a rotation by negation, and uses that to aim the axis of a uniform planar rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Multiplication of rotation matrices is homomorphic to multiplication of quaternions, and multiplication by a unit quaternion rotates the unit sphere.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Since the homomorphism is a local isometry, we immediately conclude that to produce a uniform distribution on SO(3) we may use a uniform distribution on *S*3.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] In practice: create a four-element vector where each element is a sampling of a normal distribution.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Normalize its length and you have a uniformly sampled random unit quaternion which represents a uniformly sampled random rotation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Note that the aforementioned only applies to rotations in dimension 3.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For a generalised idea of quaternions, one should look into Rotors.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] Euler angles can also be used, though not with each angle uniformly distributed (Murnaghan 1962; Miles 1965).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/rotation-matrix-p02] For the axis–angle form, the axis is uniformly distributed over the unit sphere of directions, *S*2, while the angle has the nonuniform distribution over [0,π] noted previously (Miles 1965).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In bioinformatics, a **sequence alignment** is a way of arranging the sequences of DNA, RNA, or protein to identify regions of similarity that may be a consequence of functional, structural, or evolutionary relationships between the sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Aligned sequences of nucleotide or amino acid residues are typically represented as rows within a matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Gaps are inserted between the residues so that identical or similar characters are aligned in successive columns.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments are also used for non-biological sequences such as calculating the distance cost between strings in a natural language, or to display financial data.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] If two sequences in an alignment share a common ancestor, mismatches can be interpreted as point mutations and gaps as indels (that is, insertion or deletion mutations) introduced in one or both lineages in the time since they diverged from one another.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In sequence alignments of proteins, the degree of similarity between amino acids occupying a particular position in the sequence can be interpreted as a rough measure of how conserved a particular region or sequence motif is among lineages.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The absence of substitutions, or the presence of only very conservative substitutions (that is, the substitution of amino acids whose side chains have similar biochemical properties) in a particular region of the sequence, suggest that this region has structural or functional importance.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Although DNA and RNA nucleotide bases are more similar to each other than are amino acids, the conservation of base pairs can indicate a similar functional or structural role.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Very short or very similar sequences can be aligned by hand.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] However, most interesting problems require the alignment of lengthy, highly variable or extremely numerous sequences that cannot be aligned solely by human effort.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Various algorithms were devised to produce high-quality sequence alignments, and occasionally in adjusting the final results to reflect patterns that are difficult to represent algorithmically (especially in the case of nucleotide sequences).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Computational approaches to sequence alignment generally fall into two categories: *global alignments* and *local alignments*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Calculating a global alignment is a form of global optimization that "forces" the alignment to span the entire length of all query sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] By contrast, local alignments identify regions of similarity within long sequences that are often widely divergent overall.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Local alignments are often preferable, but can be more difficult to calculate because of the additional challenge of identifying the regions of similarity.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A variety of computational algorithms have been applied to the sequence alignment problem.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] These include slow but formally correct methods like dynamic programming.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] These also include efficient, heuristic algorithms or probabilistic methods designed for large-scale database search, that do not guarantee to find best matches.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Alignments are commonly represented both graphically and in text format.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In almost all sequence alignment representations, sequences are written in rows arranged so that aligned residues appear in successive columns.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In text formats, aligned columns containing identical or similar characters are indicated with a system of conservation symbols.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] As in the image above, an asterisk or pipe symbol is used to show identity between two columns; other less common symbols include a colon for conservative substitutions and a period for semiconservative substitutions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Many sequence visualization programs also use color to display information about the properties of the individual sequence elements; in DNA and RNA sequences, this equates to assigning each nucleotide its own color.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In protein alignments, such as the one in the image above, color is often used to indicate amino acid properties to aid in judging the conservation of a given amino acid substitution.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments can be stored in a wide variety of text-based file formats, many of which were originally developed in conjunction with a specific alignment program or implementation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Most web-based tools allow a limited number of input and output formats, such as FASTA format and GenBank format and the output is not easily editable.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Several conversion programs that provide graphical and/or command line interfaces are available, such as READSEQ and EMBOSS.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] There are also several programming packages which provide this conversion functionality, such as BioPython, BioRuby and BioPerl.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The SAM/BAM files use the CIGAR (Compact Idiosyncratic Gapped Alignment Report) string format to represent an alignment of a sequence to a reference by encoding a sequence of events (e.g. match/mismatch, insertions, deletions).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The original CIGAR format from the exonerate alignment program did not distinguish between mismatches or matches with the M character.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The SAMv1 spec document defines newer CIGAR codes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In most cases it is preferred to use the '=' and 'X' characters to denote matches or mismatches rather than the older 'M' character, which is ambiguous.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Global alignments, which attempt to align every residue in every sequence, are most useful when the sequences in the query set are similar and of roughly equal size.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] (This does not mean global alignments cannot start and/or end in gaps.) A general global alignment technique is the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, which is based on dynamic programming.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Local alignments are more useful for dissimilar sequences that are suspected to contain regions of similarity or similar sequence motifs within their larger sequence context.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The Smith–Waterman algorithm is a general local alignment method based on the same dynamic programming scheme but with additional choices to start and end at any place.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Hybrid methods, known as semi-global or "glocal" (short for **glo**bal-lo**cal**) methods, search for the best possible partial alignment of the two sequences (in other words, a combination of one or both starts and one or both ends is stated to be aligned).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] This can be especially useful when the downstream part of one sequence overlaps with the upstream part of the other sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In this case, neither global nor local alignment is entirely appropriate: a global alignment would attempt to force the alignment to extend beyond the region of overlap, while a local alignment might not fully cover the region of overlap.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Another case where semi-global alignment is useful is when one sequence is short (for example a gene sequence) and the other is very long (for example a chromosome sequence).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In that case, the short sequence should be globally (fully) aligned but only a local (partial) alignment is desired for the long sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Fast expansion of genetic data challenges speed of current DNA sequence alignment algorithms.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Essential needs for an efficient and accurate method for DNA variant discovery demand innovative approaches for parallel processing in real time.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Optical computing approaches have been suggested as promising alternatives to the current electrical implementations, yet their applicability remains to be tested [1].
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Pairwise sequence alignment methods are used to find the best-matching piecewise (local or global) alignments of two query sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Pairwise alignments can only be used between two sequences at a time, but they are efficient to calculate and are often used for methods that do not require extreme precision (such as searching a database for sequences with high similarity to a query).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The three primary methods of producing pairwise alignments are dot-matrix methods, dynamic programming, and word methods; however, multiple sequence alignment techniques can also align pairs of sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Although each method has its individual strengths and weaknesses, all three pairwise methods have difficulty with highly repetitive sequences of low information content - especially where the number of repetitions differ in the two sequences to be aligned.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] One way of quantifying the utility of a given pairwise alignment is the 'maximal unique match' (MUM), or the longest subsequence that occurs in both query sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Longer MUM sequences typically reflect closer relatedness in the multiple sequence alignment of genomes in computational biology.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Identification of MUMs and other potential anchors, is the first step in larger alignment systems such as MUMmer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Anchors are the areas between two genomes where they are highly similar.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] To understand what a MUM is we can break down each word in the acronym.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Match implies that the substring occurs in both sequences to be aligned.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Unique means that the substring occurs only once in each sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Finally, maximal states that the substring is not part of another larger string that fulfills both prior requirements.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The idea behind this, is that long sequences that match exactly and occur only once in each genome are almost certainly part of the global alignment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The dot-matrix approach, which implicitly produces a family of alignments for individual sequence regions, is qualitative and conceptually simple, though time-consuming to analyze on a large scale.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In the absence of noise, it can be easy to visually identify certain sequence features—such as insertions, deletions, repeats, or inverted repeats—from a dot-matrix plot.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] To construct a dot-matrix plot, the two sequences are written along the top row and leftmost column of a two-dimensional matrix and a dot is placed at any point where the characters in the appropriate columns match—this is a typical recurrence plot.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Some implementations vary the size or intensity of the dot depending on the degree of similarity of the two characters, to accommodate conservative substitutions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The dot plots of very closely related sequences will appear as a single line along the matrix's main diagonal.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Problems with dot plots as an information display technique include: noise, lack of clarity, non-intuitiveness, difficulty extracting match summary statistics and match positions on the two sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] There is also much wasted space where the match data is inherently duplicated across the diagonal and most of the actual area of the plot is taken up by either empty space or noise, and, finally, dot-plots are limited to two sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] None of these limitations apply to Miropeats alignment diagrams but they have their own particular flaws.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Dot plots can also be used to assess repetitiveness in a single sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A sequence can be plotted against itself and regions that share significant similarities will appear as lines off the main diagonal.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] This effect occurs when a protein consists of multiple similar structural domains.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The technique of dynamic programming can be applied to produce global alignments via the Needleman-Wunsch algorithm, and local alignments via the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In typical usage, protein alignments use a substitution matrix to assign scores to amino-acid matches or mismatches, and a gap penalty for matching an amino acid in one sequence to a gap in the other.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] DNA and RNA alignments may use a scoring matrix, but in practice often simply assign a positive match score, a negative mismatch score, and a negative gap penalty.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] (In standard dynamic programming, the score of each amino acid position is independent of the identity of its neighbors, and therefore base stacking effects are not taken into account.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] However, it is possible to account for such effects by modifying the algorithm.) A common extension to standard linear gap costs are affine gap costs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Here two different gap penalties are applied for opening a gap and for extending a gap.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Typically the former is much larger than the latter, e.g. -10 for gap open and -2 for gap extension.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] This results in fewer gaps in an alignment and residues and gaps are kept together, traits more representative of biological sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The Gotoh algorithm implements affine gap costs by using three matrices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Dynamic programming can be useful in aligning nucleotide to protein sequences, a task complicated by the need to take into account frameshift mutations (usually insertions or deletions).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The framesearch method produces a series of global or local pairwise alignments between a query nucleotide sequence and a search set of protein sequences, or vice versa.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Its ability to evaluate frameshifts offset by an arbitrary number of nucleotides makes the method useful for sequences containing large numbers of indels, which can be very difficult to align with more efficient heuristic methods.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In practice, the method requires large amounts of computing power or a system whose architecture is specialized for dynamic programming.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The BLAST and EMBOSS suites provide basic tools for creating translated alignments (though some of these approaches take advantage of side-effects of sequence searching capabilities of the tools).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] More general methods are available from open-source software such as GeneWise.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The dynamic programming method is guaranteed to find an optimal alignment given a particular scoring function; however, identifying a good scoring function is often an empirical rather than a theoretical matter.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Although dynamic programming is extensible to more than two sequences, it is prohibitively slow for large numbers of sequences or extremely long sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Word methods, also known as *k*-tuple methods, are heuristic methods that are not guaranteed to find an optimal alignment solution, but are significantly more efficient than dynamic programming.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] These methods are especially useful in large-scale database searches where it is understood that a large proportion of the candidate sequences will have essentially no significant match with the query sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Word methods are best known for their implementation in the database search tools FASTA and the BLAST family.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Word methods identify a series of short, nonoverlapping subsequences ("words") in the query sequence that are then matched to candidate database sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The relative positions of the word in the two sequences being compared are subtracted to obtain an offset; this will indicate a region of alignment if multiple distinct words produce the same offset.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Only if this region is detected do these methods apply more sensitive alignment criteria; thus, many unnecessary comparisons with sequences of no appreciable similarity are eliminated.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In the FASTA method, the user defines a value *k* to use as the word length with which to search the database.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The method is slower but more sensitive at lower values of *k*, which are also preferred for searches involving a very short query sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The BLAST family of search methods provides a number of algorithms optimized for particular types of queries, such as searching for distantly related sequence matches.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] BLAST was developed to provide a faster alternative to FASTA without sacrificing much accuracy; like FASTA, BLAST uses a word search of length *k*, but evaluates only the most significant word matches, rather than every word match as does FASTA.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Most BLAST implementations use a fixed default word length that is optimized for the query and database type, and that is changed only under special circumstances, such as when searching with repetitive or very short query sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Implementations can be found via a number of web portals, such as EMBL FASTA and NCBI BLAST.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignment is an extension of pairwise alignment to incorporate more than two sequences at a time.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Multiple alignment methods try to align all of the sequences in a given query set.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Multiple alignments are often used in identifying conserved sequence regions across a group of sequences hypothesized to be evolutionarily related.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Such conserved sequence motifs can be used in conjunction with structural and mechanistic information to locate the catalytic active sites of enzymes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Alignments are also used to aid in establishing evolutionary relationships by constructing phylogenetic trees.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignments are computationally difficult to produce and most formulations of the problem lead to NP-complete combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Nevertheless, the utility of these alignments in bioinformatics has led to the development of a variety of methods suitable for aligning three or more sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The technique of dynamic programming is theoretically applicable to any number of sequences; however, because it is computationally expensive in both time and memory, it is rarely used for more than three or four sequences in its most basic form.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] This method requires constructing the *n*-dimensional equivalent of the sequence matrix formed from two sequences, where *n* is the number of sequences in the query.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Standard dynamic programming is first used on all pairs of query sequences and then the "alignment space" is filled in by considering possible matches or gaps at intermediate positions, eventually constructing an alignment essentially between each two-sequence alignment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Although this technique is computationally expensive, its guarantee of a global optimum solution is useful in cases where only a few sequences need to be aligned accurately.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] One method for reducing the computational demands of dynamic programming, which relies on the "sum of pairs" objective function, has been implemented in the MSA software package.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Progressive, hierarchical, or tree methods generate a multiple sequence alignment by first aligning the most similar sequences and then adding successively less related sequences or groups to the alignment until the entire query set has been incorporated into the solution.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The initial tree describing the sequence relatedness is based on pairwise comparisons that may include heuristic pairwise alignment methods similar to FASTA.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Progressive alignment results are dependent on the choice of "most related" sequences and thus can be sensitive to inaccuracies in the initial pairwise alignments.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Most progressive multiple sequence alignment methods additionally weight the sequences in the query set according to their relatedness, which reduces the likelihood of making a poor choice of initial sequences and thus improves alignment accuracy.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Many variations of the Clustal progressive implementation are used for multiple sequence alignment, phylogenetic tree construction, and as input for protein structure prediction.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A slower but more accurate variant of the progressive method is known as T-Coffee.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Iterative methods attempt to improve on the heavy dependence on the accuracy of the initial pairwise alignments, which is the weak point of the progressive methods.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Iterative methods optimize an objective function based on a selected alignment scoring method by assigning an initial global alignment and then realigning sequence subsets.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The realigned subsets are then themselves aligned to produce the next iteration's multiple sequence alignment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Various ways of selecting the sequence subgroups and objective function are reviewed in.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Motif finding, also known as profile analysis, constructs global multiple sequence alignments that attempt to align short conserved sequence motifs among the sequences in the query set.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] This is usually done by first constructing a general global multiple sequence alignment, after which the highly conserved regions are isolated and used to construct a set of profile matrices.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The profile matrix for each conserved region is arranged like a scoring matrix but its frequency counts for each amino acid or nucleotide at each position are derived from the conserved region's character distribution rather than from a more general empirical distribution.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The profile matrices are then used to search other sequences for occurrences of the motif they characterize.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In cases where the original data set contained a small number of sequences, or only highly related sequences, pseudocounts are added to normalize the character distributions represented in the motif.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A variety of general optimization algorithms commonly used in computer science have also been applied to the multiple sequence alignment problem.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Genetic algorithms and simulated annealing have also been used in optimizing multiple sequence alignment scores as judged by a scoring function like the sum-of-pairs method.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] More complete details and software packages can be found in the main article multiple sequence alignment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The Burrows–Wheeler transform has been successfully applied to fast short read alignment in popular tools such as Bowtie and BWA.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Structural alignments, which are usually specific to protein and sometimes RNA sequences, use information about the secondary and tertiary structure of the protein or RNA molecule to aid in aligning the sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Because both protein and RNA structure is more evolutionarily conserved than sequence, structural alignments can be more reliable between sequences that are very distantly related and that have diverged so extensively that sequence comparison cannot reliably detect their similarity.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Structural alignments are used as the "gold standard" in evaluating alignments for homology-based protein structure prediction because they explicitly align regions of the protein sequence that are structurally similar rather than relying exclusively on sequence information.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] However, clearly structural alignments cannot be used in structure prediction because at least one sequence in the query set is the target to be modeled, for which the structure is not known.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The DALI method, or distance matrix alignment, is a fragment-based method for constructing structural alignments based on contact similarity patterns between successive hexapeptides in the query sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] It can generate pairwise or multiple alignments and identify a query sequence's structural neighbors in the Protein Data Bank (PDB).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] It has been used to construct the FSSP structural alignment database (Fold classification based on Structure-Structure alignment of Proteins, or Families of Structurally Similar Proteins).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A DALI webserver can be accessed at DALI and the FSSP is located at The Dali Database.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] SSAP (sequential structure alignment program) is a dynamic programming-based method of structural alignment that uses atom-to-atom vectors in structure space as comparison points.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] It has been extended since its original description to include multiple as well as pairwise alignments, and has been used in the construction of the CATH (Class, Architecture, Topology, Homology) hierarchical database classification of protein folds.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The CATH database can be accessed at CATH Protein Structure Classification.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The combinatorial extension method of structural alignment generates a pairwise structural alignment by using local geometry to align short fragments of the two proteins being analyzed and then assembles these fragments into a larger alignment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A path from one protein structure state to the other is then traced through the matrix by extending the growing alignment one fragment at a time.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The optimal such path defines the combinatorial-extension alignment.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A web-based server implementing the method and providing a database of pairwise alignments of structures in the Protein Data Bank is located at the Combinatorial Extension website.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Phylogenetics and sequence alignment are closely related fields due to the shared necessity of evaluating sequence relatedness.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The field of phylogenetics makes extensive use of sequence alignments in the construction and interpretation of phylogenetic trees, which are used to classify the evolutionary relationships between homologous genes represented in the genomes of divergent species.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The degree to which sequences in a query set differ is qualitatively related to the sequences' evolutionary distance from one another.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Roughly speaking, high sequence identity suggests that the sequences in question have a comparatively young most recent common ancestor, while low identity suggests that the divergence is more ancient.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Therefore, it does not account for possible difference among organisms or species in the rates of DNA repair or the possible functional conservation of specific regions in a sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] More statistically accurate methods allow the evolutionary rate on each branch of the phylogenetic tree to vary, thus producing better estimates of coalescence times for genes.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Progressive multiple alignment techniques produce a phylogenetic tree by necessity because they incorporate sequences into the growing alignment in order of relatedness.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Other techniques that assemble multiple sequence alignments and phylogenetic trees score and sort trees first and calculate a multiple sequence alignment from the highest-scoring tree.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Commonly used methods of phylogenetic tree construction are mainly heuristic because the problem of selecting the optimal tree, like the problem of selecting the optimal multiple sequence alignment, is NP-hard.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments are useful in bioinformatics for identifying sequence similarity, producing phylogenetic trees, and developing homology models of protein structures.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] However, the biological relevance of sequence alignments is not always clear.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In database searches such as BLAST, statistical methods can determine the likelihood of a particular alignment between sequences or sequence regions arising by chance given the size and composition of the database being searched.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] These values can vary significantly depending on the search space.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In particular, the likelihood of finding a given alignment by chance increases if the database consists only of sequences from the same organism as the query sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Repetitive sequences in the database or query can also distort both the search results and the assessment of statistical significance; BLAST automatically filters such repetitive sequences in the query to avoid apparent hits that are statistical artifacts.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Methods of statistical significance estimation for gapped sequence alignments are available in the literature.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Statistical significance indicates the probability that an alignment of a given quality could arise by chance, but does not indicate how much superior a given alignment is to alternative alignments of the same sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Measures of alignment credibility indicate the extent to which the best scoring alignments for a given pair of sequences are substantially similar.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Methods of alignment credibility estimation for gapped sequence alignments are available in the literature.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The choice of a scoring function that reflects biological or statistical observations about known sequences is important to producing good alignments.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Protein sequences are frequently aligned using substitution matrices that reflect the probabilities of given character-to-character substitutions.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A series of matrices called PAM matrices (Point Accepted Mutation matrices, originally defined by Margaret Dayhoff and sometimes referred to as "Dayhoff matrices") explicitly encode evolutionary approximations regarding the rates and probabilities of particular amino acid mutations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Another common series of scoring matrices, known as BLOSUM (Blocks Substitution Matrix), encodes empirically derived substitution probabilities.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Variants of both types of matrices are used to detect sequences with differing levels of divergence, thus allowing users of BLAST or FASTA to restrict searches to more closely related matches or expand to detect more divergent sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Gap penalties account for the introduction of a gap - on the evolutionary model, an insertion or deletion mutation - in both nucleotide and protein sequences, and therefore the penalty values should be proportional to the expected rate of such mutations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The quality of the alignments produced therefore depends on the quality of the scoring function.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] It can be very useful and instructive to try the same alignment several times with different choices for scoring matrix and/or gap penalty values and compare the results.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Regions where the solution is weak or non-unique can often be identified by observing which regions of the alignment are robust to variations in alignment parameters.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Sequenced RNA, such as expressed sequence tags and full-length mRNAs, can be aligned to a sequenced genome to find where there are genes and get information about alternative splicing and RNA editing.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignment is also a part of genome assembly, where sequences are aligned to find overlap so that *contigs* (long stretches of sequence) can be formed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Another use is SNP analysis, where sequences from different individuals are aligned to find single basepairs that are often different in a population.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The methods used for biological sequence alignment have also found applications in other fields, most notably in natural language processing and in social sciences, where the Needleman-Wunsch algorithm is usually referred to as Optimal matching.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Techniques that generate the set of elements from which words will be selected in natural-language generation algorithms have borrowed multiple sequence alignment techniques from bioinformatics to produce linguistic versions of computer-generated mathematical proofs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] In the field of historical and comparative linguistics, sequence alignment has been used to partially automate the comparative method by which linguists traditionally reconstruct languages.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Business and marketing research has also applied multiple sequence alignment techniques in analyzing series of purchases over time.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A more complete list of available software categorized by algorithm and alignment type is available at sequence alignment software, but common software tools used for general sequence alignment tasks include ClustalW2 and T-coffee for alignment, and BLAST and FASTA3x for database searching.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Commercial tools such as DNASTAR Lasergene, Geneious, and PatternHunter are also available.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Tools annotated as performing sequence alignment are listed in the bio.tools registry.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] Alignment algorithms and software can be directly compared to one another using a standardized set of benchmark reference multiple sequence alignments known as BAliBASE.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The data set consists of structural alignments, which can be considered a standard against which purely sequence-based methods are compared.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] The relative performance of many common alignment methods on frequently encountered alignment problems has been tabulated and selected results published online at BAliBASE.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/sequence-alignment] A comprehensive list of BAliBASE scores for many (currently 12) different alignment tools can be computed within the protein workbench STRAP.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] In natural language processing, a **word embedding** is a representation of a word.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes the meaning of the word in such a way that the words that are closer in the vector space are expected to be similar in meaning.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Word embeddings can be obtained using language modeling and feature learning techniques, where words or phrases from the vocabulary are mapped to vectors of real numbers.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Methods to generate this mapping include neural networks, dimensionality reduction on the word co-occurrence matrix, probabilistic models, explainable knowledge base method, and explicit representation in terms of the context in which words appear.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Word and phrase embeddings, when used as the underlying input representation, have been shown to boost the performance in NLP tasks such as syntactic parsing and sentiment analysis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] In distributional semantics, a quantitative methodological approach for understanding meaning in observed language, word embeddings or semantic feature space models have been used as a knowledge representation for some time.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Such models aim to quantify and categorize semantic similarities between linguistic items based on their distributional properties in large samples of language data.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] The underlying idea that "a word is characterized by the company it keeps" was proposed in a 1957 article by John Rupert Firth, but also has roots in the contemporaneous work on search systems and in cognitive psychology.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] The first generation of semantic space models is the vector space model for information retrieval.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Such vector space models for words and their distributional data implemented in their simplest form results in a very sparse vector space of high dimensionality (cf. curse of dimensionality).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Reducing the number of dimensions using linear algebraic methods such as singular value decomposition then led to the introduction of latent semantic analysis in the late 1980s and the random indexing approach for collecting word co-occurrence contexts.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] In 2000, Bengio et al. provided in a series of papers titled "Neural probabilistic language models" to reduce the high dimensionality of word representations in contexts by "learning a distributed representation for words".
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] A study published in NeurIPS (NIPS) 2002 introduced the use of both word and document embeddings applying the method of kernel CCA to bilingual (and multi-lingual) corpora, also providing an early example of self-supervised learning of word embeddings.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Word embeddings come in two different styles, one in which words are expressed as vectors of co-occurring words, and another in which words are expressed as vectors of linguistic contexts in which the words occur; these different styles are studied in Lavelli et al., 2004.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Roweis and Saul published in *Science* how to use "locally linear embedding" (LLE) to discover representations of high dimensional data structures.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Most new word embedding techniques after about 2005 rely on a neural network architecture instead of more probabilistic and algebraic models, after foundational work done by Yoshua Bengio and colleagues.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] The approach has been adopted by many research groups after theoretical advances in 2010 had been made on the quality of vectors and the training speed of the model, as well as after hardware advances allowed for a broader parameter space to be explored profitably.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] In 2013, a team at Google led by Tomas Mikolov created word2vec, a word embedding toolkit that can train vector space models faster than previous approaches.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] The word2vec approach has been widely used in experimentation and was instrumental in raising interest for word embeddings as a technology, moving the research strand out of specialised research into broader experimentation and eventually paving the way for practical application.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Historically, one of the main limitations of static word embeddings or word vector space models is that words with multiple meanings are conflated into a single representation (a single vector in the semantic space).
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] In other words, polysemy and homonymy are not handled properly.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] For example, in the sentence "The club I tried yesterday was great!", it is not clear if the term *club* is related to the word sense of a *club sandwich*, *clubhouse*, *golf club*, or any other sense that *club* might have.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] The necessity to accommodate multiple meanings per word in different vectors (multi-sense embeddings) is the motivation for several contributions in NLP to split single-sense embeddings into multi-sense ones.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Most approaches that produce multi-sense embeddings can be divided into two main categories for their word sense representation, i.e., unsupervised and knowledge-based.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Based on word2vec skip-gram, Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (MSSG) performs word-sense discrimination and embedding simultaneously, improving its training time, while assuming a specific number of senses for each word.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] In the Non-Parametric Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (NP-MSSG) this number can vary depending on each word.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Once the words are disambiguated, they can be used in a standard word embeddings technique, so multi-sense embeddings are produced.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] MSSA architecture allows the disambiguation and annotation process to be performed recurrently in a self-improving manner.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] The use of multi-sense embeddings is known to improve performance in several NLP tasks, such as part-of-speech tagging, semantic relation identification, semantic relatedness, named entity recognition and sentiment analysis.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] As of the late 2010s, contextually-meaningful embeddings such as ELMo and BERT have been developed.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] Unlike static word embeddings, these embeddings are at the token-level, in that each occurrence of a word has its own embedding.
[src:rotary-position-embedding/word-embedding] These embeddings better reflect the multi-sense nature of words, because occurrences of a word in similar contexts are situated in similar regions of BERT's embedding space.
